<DOC><DOCNO> AP881226-0172 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-12-26-88 2008EST</FILEID><FIRST>d f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   12-26 0529</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0553</SECOND><NOTE>Eds: for Tuesday PMs</NOTE><DATELINE>OTTAWA (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The House of Commons has approved and sent to theCanadian Senate the Canada-U.S. free trade agreement.   The sweeping legislation approved Saturday will begin breakingdown trade and business barriers with the United States as early asNew Year's Day.   In Washington, a U.S. administration trade official welcomed theCommons vote, saying the trade pact would spur economic growth onboth sides of the border.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Americans believe President Reagan has helped therich and hurt the poor, but a wide majority nonetheless approve ofhis work in the White House, according to a national poll.   Majorities in the Media General-Associated Press survey gavenegative grades to Reagan's social policies and ethics enforcement,rated his judgment unfavorably and said they would not havesupported him for a third term.   The poll found two factors at the heart of Reagan's popularity:Wide belief that his economic policies have helped the nation andhigh regard for his leadership.</TEXT><DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   CSX Corp. says it will sell its Texas GasTransmission Co. pipeline subsidiary and two related companies toTransco Energy Co. for $646 million.   The sale of Texas Gas, which operates a 6,000-mile pipelinesystem extending from the Gulf of Mexico and East Texas througheight other states, is part of CSX's continued restructuring.   Transco agreed to pay $571 million for the natural gas pipelineoperations, plus an additional $75 million cash dividend to CSXprior to closing. The deal was announced Friday.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   American Brands Inc. was closed for the Christmasholiday, but that didn't stop Wall Street from briefly sending thetobacco company's stock up 22 percent on rumors of a takeover byUnilever, the British-Dutch consumer products conglomerate.   Both companies declined to discuss Friday's rumors. According toone rumor, Unilever might pay as much as $90 a share for AmericanBrands.   American Brands rose as high as $70.25 a share and was at $67.12{in late trading on Wall Street, up $9.50, or 16 percent.</TEXT><DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Ford Motor Co. reported a 35.9 percent leap in carsales in mid-December as the Big Three automakers said their overallcar and light truck sales were up 15.3 percent from the same periodin 1987.   The companies said Friday they sold an average of 33,081 vehiclesin each of the eight selling days from Dec. 11-20, up from 28,689 aday in the eight sales days of the comparable 1987 period.   Chrysler Corp. said its car sales were up 20.5 percent whileGeneral Motors Corp. reported its car sales rose 4.7 percent.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The settlement of fraud charges by Wall Streetpowerhouse Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. isn't expected to bring amajor shakeup in the market for junk bonds pioneered and dominatedby Drexel.   Still, market players are taking a cautious, wait-and-seeattitude.   U.S. Attorney Rudolph W. Giuliani announced last week that Drexelhad reversed itself by agreeing to admit guilt to six felonies andpay a record $650 million fine to settle the biggest securitiesfraud case in history.</TEXT><NOTE>MORE</NOTE></DOC>